description:
The Pi extension's HTTP client (`extensions/pi-synchronize/src/client.ts`) captures the daemon `baseUrl` at startup time via `discoverDaemon()` and uses that cached value for the lifetime of the Pi process. When the daemon is restarted (it gets a new random port), Pi's subsequent heartbeats, subscriptions, and outbound calls all hit the dead port and fail with `fetch failed`.

## Evidence — 2026-05-23 manual session

After a daemon restart from port 58254 → 54067, karel's pid 90391 logged `heartbeat failed: fetch failed` every 15 seconds for at least 5 minutes. Meanwhile, the Claude-side MCP adapters (bob, alice, operator) all reconnected on their next bridge_* call without intervention. Asymmetry between Pi and Claude on the resilience story.

## Contrast — Claude side does it right

Claude's MCP adapter calls `ensureDaemon()` / `discoverDaemon()` from `src/client.ts` lazily on every HTTP request. On `ECONNREFUSED` or similar transport failures, it re-reads `~/.synchronize/daemon.json` and either picks up the new port or auto-spawns a daemon. This is what makes the hot-reload story work for Claude.

## Fix proposal

In `extensions/pi-synchronize/src/client.ts`, wrap fetch calls in a retry-with-rediscover helper:

```typescript
async function requestWithRediscover(client: PiSyncClient, path: string, init: RequestInit) {
  try {
    return await fetch(`${client.baseUrl}${path}`, init);
  } catch (error) {
    if (isConnectionError(error)) {
      const fresh = await discoverDaemon();
      client.baseUrl = fresh.baseUrl;
      return await fetch(`${client.baseUrl}${path}`, init);
    }
    throw error;
  }
}
```

Also add a `re-registering peer after daemon restart` path: if a heartbeat returns `peer_not_found`, re-run `registerPeer` with the same `peer_id`. The daemon's INSERT ... ON CONFLICT(peer_id) DO UPDATE already handles this idempotently.

## Why P1

This bug ALONE causes Pi agents to silently fall off the bus on daemon restart, with no recovery without operator intervention (kill + relaunch). Combined with sync-dmc (peer cascade-delete) the impact cascades — group_members rows vanish too. We hit this exact failure twice in one session.

The `synchronize launch pi --name <NAME>` CLI flag is silently ignored by the Pi extension. The launch wrapper correctly forwards `SYNCHRONIZE_SESSION_NAME=<NAME>` to the spawned Pi process, but `extensions/pi-synchronize/src/identity.ts:resolveSessionName` checks `piSessionId` first and returns `pi-<piSessionId>` whenever Pi has a session (always). The env name is only used when piSessionId is absent.

## Evidence

User launched `synchronize launch pi --name karel`. Pi extension log at `~/.synchronize/pi-extension.log`:

```
2026-05-23T00:04:47.184Z [synchronize-pi] pid=15716 registered
  peer_id=1c21ac84-… session_name=pi-019e5226-0e8d-7439-aa6d-2db1386bc5a0
```

Expected: `session_name=karel`. Got: `pi-019e5226-…`.

## Root cause

```typescript
// extensions/pi-synchronize/src/identity.ts
export function resolveSessionName(hints: IdentityHints = {}): string {
  if (hints.piSessionId && hints.piSessionId.length > 0) return `pi-${hints.piSessionId}`;
  if (hints.envSessionName && hints.envSessionName.length > 0) return hints.envSessionName;
  // …random fallback…
}
```

## Fix proposal

Swap the order so env name wins:

```typescript
if (hints.envSessionName && hints.envSessionName.length > 0) return hints.envSessionName;
if (hints.piSessionId && hints.piSessionId.length > 0) return `pi-${hints.piSessionId}`;
```

Rationale: `--name` is explicit user intent; `pi-<sessionId>` is the no-intent fallback.

## Secondary mystery (separate ticket if confirmed)

Despite the extension registering as `pi-019e5226-…`, the user's `bridge_whoami` reportedly returned `agent`. This suggests the Pi LLM may be self-renaming via `bridge_register` or `bridge_rename_session` despite skill instructions. Needs Pi transcript inspection at `~/.pi/agent/sessions/`.
